pants to the heart of the Rocky Mountains. The price for admission for most was a pledge to give at least $100,000 this year to the Kochs‚Äô broad policy and political network. There were also at least 18 elected officials on hand. Some hosted private policy discussions with donors while others simply mingled.\n\nIn between meetings, Rep. Dave Brat, R-Virginia, predicted dire consequences in next year‚Äôs midterm elections should his party fail to deliver on its repeated promises.\n\n‚ÄúIf we don‚Äôt get health care, none of us are coming back,‚Äù he said in a brief interview. ‚ÄúWe said for seven years you‚Äôre gonna repeal Obamacare. It‚Äôs nowhere near repealed.‚Äù\n\nIt‚Äôs the same for tax reform, Brat said: ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt get taxes through, we‚Äôre all going home. Pack the bags.‚Äù\n\nThere was a sense of deep frustration from conservative officials and donors alike in some cases, who decried the pace of progress in Washington with Republicans controlling both chambers of Congress and the White House for the first time in a decade.\n\nTexas-based donor Doug Deason has already informed a handful of congressional Republicans that the ‚ÄúDallas piggy bank‚Äù is closed until he sees more action. He said he was recently approached by Rep. Mark Meadows, R-N.C. and Rep. Jim Jordan, R-Ohio, about hosting a fundraiser.\n\n‚ÄúI said, ‚ÄòNo I‚Äôm not going to because we‚Äôre closing the checkbook until you get some things done,‚Äô‚Äù Deason said, noting he‚Äôs encouraged nearly two dozen major Texas donors to follow his lead.\n\n‚ÄúGet Obamacare repealed and replaced, get tax reform passed,‚Äù Deason continued. ‚ÄúGet it done and we‚Äôll open it back up.‚Äù\n\nWhile some donors threatened to withhold campaign cash, Koch‚Äôs team outlined a broader strategy to help shape the debate.\n\nAlready, Americans For Prosperity claims a paid staff of more than 400 full-time activists in 36 states. Koch officials said that the network‚Äôs midterm budget for policy and politics is be