1086	LA native finds home, job at Sweetwater Sound in Fort Wayne			http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jun/26/la-native-finds-home-job-at-sweetwater-sound-in-fo/	\N	FORT WAYNE, Ind.\n‚ÄúIt was a very cool job.‚Äù In 2013, the show won the New York Drama Desk Award for Unique Theatrical Experience.\n‚ÄúIn the three years I‚Äôve been here, this town has exploded,‚Äù he says of Fort Wayne.\n‚ÄúI told my wife, ‚ÄòSo, you want to move to Fort Wayne, Indiana?‚Äô And she says there‚Äôs no way we‚Äôre moving to Fort Wayne, Indiana.\n___Source: The (Fort Wayne) Journal Gazette, http://bit.ly/2sJELqn___Information from: The Journal Gazette, http://www.journalgazette.net	FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) - Nick D‚ÄôVirgilio has a sore back.\n\nThe drummer at Sweetwater Sound isn‚Äôt trying to conceal it, either. When he stands, he arches backward and puts both hands behind his waist, the way old people do when they roll out of bed and stretch. Walking toward the company‚Äôs nearly football field-size cafeteria in a black T-shirt and jeans, he says he‚Äôs 48, ‚Äúbut my back feels like I‚Äôm 68 right now.‚Äù\n\nIt is Monday morning at Sweetwater. Warm outside. Hot, actually. In the spacious front lobby, a group of students gathers around the now-famous two-tone Volkswagen minibus. They listen as the tour guide tells the familiar bus-to-business success story - of how founder Chuck Surack started the company from this very vehicle almost 40 years ago and turned it into a musical empire.\n\nNot content with being one of the world‚Äôs largest retail distributors of instruments, Sweetwater evolved into other interests and resources: in-store merchandise, a musical academy for students, state-of-the-art recording studios with professional in-house musicians. And this is where Nick D‚ÄôVirgilio entered the Sweetwater team picture nearly three years ago.\n\nLet‚Äôs back up, first.\n\nWhen his jet-black hair was a little longer and his two-day stubble not as white, D‚ÄôVirgilio helped form the Los Angeles progressive rock group called Spock‚Äôs Beard and was with it for almost 20 years, from 1992 until he left in 2010 as its lead singer. During that time, Spock‚Äôs Beard - the name‚Äôs a takeoff on a ‚ÄúStar Trek‚Äù episode - recorded 10 albums.\n\nBecause the group recorded sporadically, D‚ÄôVirgilio sought more work and was hired to play with British pop-rock band Tears for Fears, from 1995 to 2010. There were earlier gigs, too. He was recruited to play with Genesis, after Phil Collins left, and played on the album ‚ÄúCalling All Stations.‚Äù He‚Äôs also played with Sheryl Crow, Peter Gabriel, Eric Burdon and the Animals and Mike Keneally; and many, many others who knew of his reputation and wanted him in their studio.\n\nBut in 2011 came the Godfather offer - one he couldn‚Äôt refuse - to join Cirque du Soleil‚Äôs ‚ÄúTotem‚Äù tour as its drummer, lead singer and assistant bandleader.\n\n‚ÄúI was part of a huge rock show every night. The whole kit and caboodle; lights and smoke and the huge stage and the P.A.,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúIt was a very cool job.‚Äù In 2013, the show won the New York Drama Desk Award for Unique Theatrical Experience.\n\nNot only would he see the world, but so would his wife, Tiffany, and their children Anthony and Sophia.\n\n‚ÄúThey housed my family, schooled my kids, the whole nine yards,‚Äù D‚ÄôVirgilio says. ‚ÄúAll you had to do was pay for your kids and your family to get from A to B. You got the apartment, the whole thing. It was a fantastic benefit.\n\n‚ÄúBut they cut that (benefit), and that was my ticket out. I could‚Äôve kept my job, but I would‚Äôve had to home-school the kids in Australia and pay for their housing. It wasn‚Äôt very realistic, especially for high school-age kids. So I was looking for a job.‚Äù\n\nBecause the music world is a small one, it‚Äôs always good to know somebody. That somebody was Nashville producer/recording engineer Mark Hornsby, whom Sweetwater hired five years ago to inject new blood and fresh ideas into its studio development. Since Sweetwater was bringing in top-tier musicians, and word got out that D‚ÄôVirgilio was looking, it was a match made in Fort Wayne.\n\nIn the three years away from the hotels, motels and sideshows of ‚Äúthe road,‚Äù his world has been as steady as his drumbeat.\n\nTiffany has a job at Lutheran Hospital as a nuclear medicine technologist. Sophia, 19, recently graduated from Homestead High School and will soon be headed to Indiana University in Bloomington to study radiation therapy. Anthony, 17, will be a senior at Homestead. Both kids love the theater. Tiffany loves her three horses.\n\nWhich brings us back to D‚ÄôVirgilio‚Äôs back.\n\n‚ÄúI was moving hay,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúStacking hay. They (the horses) got to eat, and they do that quite a bit. It‚Äôs a lot of work. Luckily, my neighbor down the street has an enormous barn and he stores most of it, but it was time to get out the old and bring in the new. That‚Äôs what I did (Sunday). It was fine while I was doing it. It‚Äôs the after-effects that‚Äôs kicking my butt right now.‚Äù\n\nThankfully, his Monday schedule was a light one. A local guitar player was in Studio A, working on a song, which gave D‚ÄôVirgilio time to talk and stretch a bit.\n\nHe spends most days doing studio sessions and appearing in web videos for drum products whose makers would love to have the Sweetwater seal of approval. That‚Äôs him, playing and selling and talking up the product. ‚ÄúI get to make records and play with gear all day long,‚Äù he says.\n\nDon‚Äôt misinterpret his day-to-day contentment. D‚ÄôVirgilio stresses that he‚Äôs not Mr. Nine-to-Five. He‚Äôs the guy wearing the black T-shirt, remember, and not a Windsor knot, and that he‚Äôs still active in a few bands.\n\nThere‚Äôs the progressive rock group called Big Big Train that‚Äôs doing well on the U.K. charts and just released a new album in April called ‚ÄúGrimspound.‚Äù And he‚Äôs with the rock trio The Fringe ‚Äúto make something new,‚Äù according to its Facebook page.\n\nMeanwhile, if the phone rings, he‚Äôs up for some freelance. In September, he says, he‚Äôll be in England. He‚Äôs also been offered to play in a drum festival ‚Äúin Romania, of all places.‚Äù\n\nBad back and all, D‚ÄôVirgilio says he‚Äôs still a rocker, and not necessarily ready to sit in one.\n\n‚ÄúIt‚Äôs different,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúI miss the road. I miss playing every night for my only job. I play here quite a bit, but not like that. I do miss it. I don‚Äôt know if I will ever not miss it.\n\n‚ÄúI‚Äôm totally playing it by ear,‚Äù says D‚ÄôVirgilio, unaware, perhaps, of the double meaning. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm taking advantage of this job, which has given me lots of cool opportunities, and growing in the company and growing in this field.‚Äù\n\nHe is still L.A.-hypnotic hip. It‚Äôs where he‚Äôs from. Where Tiffany is from. Where the parents live, where the kids were small, where he coached little league and hoops, where his beloved Dodgers play. Now look at him - the SoCal boy who has a place near Roanoke, of all places.\n\nIndiana winters aside, he‚Äôs adjusting. Seriously.\n\n‚ÄúIn the three years I‚Äôve been here, this town has exploded,‚Äù he says of Fort Wayne. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs growing like crazy. There‚Äôs a lot of cool and - quote-unquote - very hip things that are coming to town as far as food, venues, music. There‚Äôs a lot of stuff going on in this city that I never would have expected.\n\n‚ÄúI told my wife, ‚ÄòSo, you want to move to Fort Wayne, Indiana?‚Äô And she says there‚Äôs no way we‚Äôre moving to Fort Wayne, Indiana. She‚Äôll tell you now it‚Äôs one of the best decisions we‚Äôve ever made. It‚Äôs one of the cool towns. It‚Äôs got so much going for it - Sweetwater being one of them - and it seems like a town that wants to push the envelope and grow, which is a cool thing for me. There are a lot of musicians in this town; a lot of art I never would have expected. Theater. All kinds of stuff going on.‚Äù\n\nAnd that ain‚Äôt hay.\n\n