1095	What‚Äôs happened to the pro-gun wish list in Washington?		http://media.washtimes.com.s3.amazonaws.com/media/image/2017/06/26/whither_the_gun_agenda_81100.jpg	http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jun/26/whats-happened-to-the-pro-gun-wish-list-in-washing/	\N	ATLANTA (AP) - Gun rights advocates entered the Trump era with high hopes.\nAfter years of frustration they thought a gun-friendly president and Congress would advance their agenda.\nAt the top of the list is a gun-owner‚Äôs ability to bring a legal weapon across any state lines.\nBut many of their favorite initiatives have stalled in Washington as the city seethes with scandal over investigations into President Donald Trump‚Äôs administration.\nGun rights may also be on the back burner because they are a heavy lift.	ATLANTA (AP) - Gun rights advocates entered the Trump era with high hopes. After years of frustration they thought a gun-friendly president and Congress would advance their agenda. At the top of the list is a gun-owner‚Äôs ability to bring a legal weapon across any state lines.\n\nBut many of their favorite initiatives have stalled in Washington as the city seethes with scandal over investigations into President Donald Trump‚Äôs administration. Republicans are focused on other priorities, especially health care. Gun rights may also be on the back burner because they are a heavy lift.\n\nCongress faces a public weary of the drumbeat of mass shootings, terror attacks and random violence. A recent Pew study also showed Americans pretty much split on support for gun control.	2017-06-26 11:39:40.247692+03	0	0	0	0	\N	\N	6	740	['The Washington Times Http', 'Lisa Marie Pane']
1096	Oolitic‚Äôs Empire Quarry considered ‚Äòsource of pride‚Äô			http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jun/26/oolitics-empire-quarry-considered-source-of-pride/	\N	On Wednesday, the Lawrence County Tourism Commission hosted a tour of Indiana Limestone Co.‚Äôs facility and Empire Quarry in Oolitic.\nFor Rizzo, it was his first quarry tour.\n‚ÄúI liked seeing the cutting of the stones, and all the equipment.‚ÄùThe Empire Quarry has been in operation for more than 80 years.\n‚ÄúMy grandfather, Thomas Abel, was head blacksmith for Indiana Limestone back in the 1920s and 1930s.\n‚Ä¶ We have a real history here.‚ÄùA sense of pride was felt by some people as they overlooked the operation at Empire Quarry.	OOLITIC, Ind. (AP) - While limestone mining isn‚Äôt exactly a foreign concept to many Lawrence County residents, it‚Äôs not something out-of-state folks see every day.\n\nOn Wednesday, the Lawrence County Tourism Commission hosted a tour of Indiana Limestone Co.‚Äôs facility and Empire Quarry in Oolitic. The company has produced limestone used for the Empire State Building in New York, the Pentagon and Yankee Stadium.\n\nMary Duerksen, an Ann Arbor, Michigan, resident who was visiting her daughter, Kelsey, of Bloomington, said she‚Äôs fallen in love with Indiana, so the tour seemed like a good way to learn about the state‚Äôs important limestone history.\n\n‚ÄúI thought this would be a great opportunity,‚Äù Duerksen said. ‚ÄúI just never understood the whole concept (of limestone), as we don‚Äôt really do a lot of mining in Michigan. My only reference was ‚ÄòBreaking Away.‚Äô It‚Äôs so amazing how they handle it back here, and it was amazing to see (Empire Quarry).‚Äù\n\nTom Rizzo, a Long Island, New York, resident who was also visiting family in Indiana, brought his grandson Maksim along for the tour. For Rizzo, it was his first quarry tour. Like Duerksen, he wasn‚Äôt too familiar with limestone history.\n\n‚ÄúWe‚Äôve enjoyed seeing all this,‚Äù Rizzo said. ‚ÄúI liked seeing the cutting of the stones, and all the equipment.‚Äù\n\nThe Empire Quarry has been in operation for more than 80 years. Indiana Limestone has about 4,500 acres of property between Lawrence and Monroe counties. The company estimates it has about 150 years of known limestone reserves.\n\nThe tour also played into various interests of the attendees. Some, especially those who grew up in the area, noted the nostalgia of the tour.\n\nPaula Patton, a Bloomington resident, said it was nice to see a quarry ‚Äúwith permission‚Äù this time, alluding to the popularity of using quarries as a swimming hole. The practice is dangerous and is generally considered trespassing.\n\n‚ÄúI‚Äôm a Hoosier ‚Ä¶ I swam in the quarries growing up,‚Äù Patton said. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs great coming back here with permission. I could do this all day long.‚Äù\n\nFor Gene Abel, a Lawrence County resident who has been working to restore limestone works in the Green Hill Cemetery, the tour made him think about his family‚Äôs connections to the limestone industry. He‚Äôs been on tours, but it was his first time on a tour of the Indiana Limestone Co.‚Äôs modern Oolitic operations.\n\n‚ÄúIt‚Äôs been enjoyable and it‚Äôs educational for me to see all these changes,‚Äù Abel said. ‚ÄúMy grandfather, Thomas Abel, was head blacksmith for Indiana Limestone back in the 1920s and 1930s. And my dad was a blacksmith after him. ‚Ä¶ It was a big business back then, but now it‚Äôs modernized. That‚Äôs what happens, though. ‚Ä¶ We have a real history here.‚Äù\n\nA sense of pride was felt by some people as they overlooked the operation at Empire Quarry. Lloyd Harry, from Evansville, said he visited quarries in Italy about five years ago, but there‚Äôs an extra sense of pride at a more local one.\n\n‚ÄúIt‚Äôs some cool stuff,‚Äù Harry said. ‚ÄúThe limestone‚Äôs been used for the state capitols, the Pentagon, the (Washington) National Cathedral ‚Ä¶ that‚Äôs definitely a source of pride.‚Äù\n\n___\n\nSource: The (Bedford) 