s shut down. And on Facebook, he mused about the possibility of being ‚Äúunjustly imprisoned.‚Äù\n\nThe 34-year-old Shkreli ‚Äútravels to the beat of a very unique drummer,‚Äù exasperated-sounding defense attorney Benjamin Brafman said at a pretrial hearing this month.\n\nLegal experts say there are obvious reasons lawyers want clients facing serious criminal charges to keep quiet.\n\n‚ÄúIt‚Äôs twofold: You don‚Äôt want to antagonize the judge and you don‚Äôt want to get the attention of the jury in a way that hurts your case,‚Äù said veteran New York City defense attorney Gerald Lefcourt.\n\nColumbia law professor John Coffee compared the situation to President Donald Trump‚Äôs unruly tweeting habits. ‚ÄúA lawyer can caution him,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúBut just like Trump, he doesn‚Äôt have to listen.‚Äù\n\nThough Shkreli‚Äôs notoriety came from Daraprim, the federal securities fraud case is unrelated. Prosecutors say that after Shkreli lost millions of dollars through bad trades through his side business hedge fund, he looted a second pharmaceutical company for $11 million to pay them back. The defense has argued that he had good intentions.\n\n‚ÄúEverybody got paid back in this case,‚Äù his lawyer said. ‚ÄúWhatever else he did wrong, he ultimately made them whole.‚Äù\n\nThe defense has floated the possibility that it would put Shkreli on the witness stand to try to highlight how he grew up in a working-class Albanian family in Brooklyn, taught himself chemistry, interned at a financial firm founded by CNBC‚Äôs Jim Cramer and struck out on his own to become a rising star in biotechnology startups. He wanted to develop new life-saving drugs after seeing ‚Äúseveral classmates and other children he knew struck down by debilitating disease,‚Äù court papers say.\n\nProsecutors call it a ploy to portray the boyish-looking Shkreli as ‚Äúa Horatio Alger-like figure who, through hard work and intelligence, is in a position to do great things if only the jury would ignore the evidence and base its verdict on sympathy.‚Äù The real Shkreli was a con man often undone by his own mouth, they say.\n\nThe government has cited claims by one of Shkreli‚Äôs former employees that Shkreli harassed his family in a dispute over shares of stock.\n\n‚ÄúI hope to see you and your four children homeless and will do whatever I can to assure this,‚Äù Shkreli wrote the employee‚Äôs wife, according to court filings.\n\nProsecutors also used his boasts about some of his purchases of eccentric collectibles to undermine efforts to reduce his bail from $5 million to $2 million. If he needed to raise cash to pay legal fees and back taxes, they argued, why not sell the one-of-a-kind Wu-Tang Clan album that he brought for $2 million or his Nazi-era Engima code-breaking machine?\n\nAlso cited were his offers to pay a $100,000 bounty for finding the killer of a Democratic National Committee staffer and $40,000 in tuition for a Princeton student who solved a math problem he posed during a guest lecture at the school earlier this year.\n\nShkreli ‚Äúis not the demon he‚Äôs been made out to be,‚Äù the student, Yuan Wang, told the AP.\n\nStill, he added, ‚ÄúI haven‚Äôt received the money yet.‚Äù	2017-06-26 11:39:55.999205+03	0	0	0	0	\N	\N	6	744	['The Washington Times Http', 'Tom Hays']
