s. In 2012, the British Museum and Radio 4 teamed up again for Shakespeare‚Äôs Restless World, a project which examined Shakespeare‚Äôs era and work through 20 objects. But these radio shows are just part of a growing fashion for telling stories through objects. ‚ÄúObject narratives‚Äù such as Edmund de Waal‚Äôs The Hare With Amber Eyes and Paula Byrne‚Äôs recent biography The Real Jane Austen: A Life in Small Things promise to replace the subjective histories we are used to with something more concrete, more trustworthy. Byrne describes Austen as ‚Äúthe most elusive of all our great writers with the exception of Shakespeare.‚Äù And the more shadowy or otherwise ungraspable the subject‚ÄîShakespeare, Austen, the whole daunting 2 million year history of humanity‚Äîthe greater the appeal of a narrative which starts with the tangible.	2017-06-26 23:32:35.243881+03	0	0	0	0	\N	\N	38	1024	
