1423	Review: Fact outhits fiction in ‚ÄòPride of the Yankees‚Äô book		http://media.washtimes.com.s3.amazonaws.com/media/image/2017/06/26/book_review_the_pride_of_the_yankees_50642.jpg	http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jun/26/review-fact-outhits-fiction-in-pride-of-the-yankee/	\N	‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees: Lou Gehrig, Gary Cooper, and the Making of a Classic‚Äù (Hachette), by Richard SandomirThe movie ‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees‚Äù is the kind of Hollywood hokum that makes us feel good.\nAnd there‚Äôs nothing wrong with that - as long as we know life is usually more complicated than a Gary Cooper movie.\n‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees‚Äù is best remembered for Cooper re-enacting Gehrig‚Äôs farewell speech at Yankee Stadium.\nOverall, he still judges ‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees‚Äù to be a classic that‚Äôs true in spirit to its subject.\nIn reel life, Cooper speaks the line at the end - the filmmakers knew a good wrap-up when they heard one.	‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees: Lou Gehrig, Gary Cooper, and the Making of a Classic‚Äù (Hachette), by Richard Sandomir\n\nThe movie ‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees‚Äù is the kind of Hollywood hokum that makes us feel good. And there‚Äôs nothing wrong with that - as long as we know life is usually more complicated than a Gary Cooper movie.\n\nRecommending a making-of-the-movie book as more interesting than the film it explores is a compliment to the author. And in the case of this 1942 biopic about baseball great Lou Gehrig, an acknowledgement that time can be cruel to our youthful favorites.\n\n‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees‚Äù is best remembered for Cooper re-enacting Gehrig‚Äôs farewell speech at Yankee Stadium. In 1939 the slugger and first baseman was dying of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, a nerve disease soon to carry his name. His oft-quoted observation - ‚ÄúToday, I consider myself the luckiest man on the face of the earth‚Äù - set the standard for self-effacing courage.\n\nWhen Hollywood got involved in Gehrig‚Äôs story, accuracy was destined to strike out. As author Richard Sandomir explains, producer Sam Goldwyn saw a Gehrig movie in terms of typical entertainment of the period: a portrait of a heroic figure with touches of humor and romance. For Goldwyn, the element of baseball was something to be ‚Äúput up with.‚Äù\n\nThe studio publicity machine created a phony tale of a national search for the right person, whether actor or athlete, to play Gehrig. (Imagine Cary Grant, Spencer Tracy or Ronald Reagan in pinstripes.) It was all about ballyhoo because Cooper was under contract to Goldwyn and owed him a picture.\n\nTicket sales and 11 Oscar nominations (it would win for film editing) proved Goldwyn was right to steer clear, for the most part, of baseball action scenes. Viewed today, however, the film can come off as a syrupy blend of cliches, falling short of the enduring charm of ‚ÄúCasablanca‚Äù and a handful of other wartime films.\n\nNot that Sandomir sees it that way. Overall, he still judges ‚ÄúThe Pride of the Yankees‚Äù to be a classic that‚Äôs true in spirit to its subject. But that pitch is batted away by the very elements that make his book worth reading. The New York Times writer researched Gehrig‚Äôs life and the story behind the movie to provide an authoritative take on what‚Äôs factual (not that much), what‚Äôs fanciful (a whole lot) and what‚Äôs a bit of both.\n\nThe Montana-born Cooper, more at home on the range than at home plate, needed lots of batting instruction, most of it taking place behind his Los Angeles mansion. One tale has it that he broke a window at neighbor Tyrone Power‚Äôs house - twice. But Sandomir refutes the folklore that all baseball scenes featuring the right-handed Cooper were reversed so he would better resemble the lefty Gehrig. Some cinematic chicanery did take place, just not nearly as much as some have said, and Cooper managed to learn to throw with his left.\n\nA heart-tugging moment in the film comes when an ailing Gehrig, waiting for his turn at bat, realizes he can‚Äôt cut it anymore and takes himself out of the lineup, causing a shock wave in the stadium. In reality, Gehrig decided the night before and told his manager the next day. The crowd knew before the first pitch.\n\nAnd then there‚Äôs the speech. Sandomir points out that newspapers published different versions of Gehrig‚Äôs farewell and that no complete newsreel of it exists. In real life, the famous line comes near the beginning of his remarks. In reel life, Cooper speaks the line at the end - the filmmakers knew a good wrap-up when they heard one.\n\nThe movie plays down the nasty relationship between Gehrig‚Äôs mother and his wife, who traded accusations about who was responsible for his illness. It also gets wrong little details - dates, stats, lineups - that suggest simple cinema sloppiness.\n\nIf none of that really matters, then Sandomir‚Äôs dogged efforts to separate fact and fiction make for one big whiff. More likely, fans of film and baseball will appreciate his book as a welcome counterbalance to feel-good Hollywood mythmaking.\n\n___\n\nDouglass K. Daniel is the author of ‚ÄúTough as Nails: The Life and Films of Richard Brooks‚Äù (University Press of Wisconsin).	2017-06-26 23:34:14.088537+03	0	0	0	0	\N	\N	6	1079	['The Washington Times Http', 'Douglass K. Daniel']
