s fiction.‚Äù\n\nThat was one of the few sympathetic portrayals in government documents of Arnold‚Äôs sighting.\n\nIn another declassified intelligence report in July 1947, First Lt. Hal L. Eustace of the Army Air Corps put Arnold‚Äôs report as part of ‚Äúsilly-season episodes.‚Äù\n\nThe lieutenant wrote that Arnold ‚Äúseems to be reasonably well balanced, although excitable, and has no apparent ulterior motive . other than to prove he is not ‚Äònuts.‚Äô?‚Äù\n\nThe lieutenant wrote that Arnold revealed ‚Äúan antagonistic attitude toward the Army‚Äù by stating, ‚ÄúWell, if the Army doesn‚Äôt know what they are, it sure ought to be trying to find out!‚Äù\n\nBright flash lit the sky\n\nArnold‚Äôs sighting of the craft was the 1947 version of a story going viral.\n\n‚ÄúIt was a beautiful day. Just as clear as a bell,‚Äù Arnold said. He was flying from Chehalis to Yakima and decided to spend an hour or so searching for a downed C-46 Marine transport that had crashed into the southwest side of Mount Rainier.\n\nThere was a $5,000 reward for finding it.\n\nIt was at 3 p.m., he remembered, ‚Äúwhen a very bright flash lit up the plane and the sky around me.‚Äù\n\nAt first, Arnold thought it was the sun reflecting off another plane.\n\n‚ÄúBut the flash happened again, and that‚Äôs when I saw where it was coming from. It came spasmodically from a chain of nine circular-type aircraft way up from the vicinity of Mount Rainier,‚Äù said Arnold.\n\n‚Äú. I could not find any tails on these things. They didn‚Äôt leave a jet trail behind them. I judged their size to be at least 100 feet in widespan. I thought it was a new type of missile.‚Äù\n\nHis plane had a big sweep 24-hour clock on the instrument panel. Arnold measured that the craft covered the distance between Mount Rainier and Mount Adams in 1 minute 42 seconds.\n\n‚ÄúThat figured out to something like 1,760 miles an hour, which I could hardly believe. I knew that figure couldn‚Äôt be entirely accurate, but I‚Äôd say it was within a couple of hundred miles accurate,‚Äù he said.\n\nFrom Yakima, Arnold then flew to an air show in Pendleton, Oregon. The next day, on June 25, he stopped by the local newspaper, the East Oregonian. He wanted to know if the military had been testing secret warplanes in the area.\n\nHe ended up talking to reporter Bill Bequette, who, in subsequent years, remembered that Arnold ‚Äúcame off as honest, level headed and credible,‚Äù said a story in the East Oregonian.\n\nSo Bequette wrote a brief story about what Arnold said he witnessed.\n\nBut the brief also went out to The Associated Press, got picked up by numerous newspapers, and the furor began. For the first time, a mass-media story and subsequent headlines used the term, ‚Äúflying saucers.‚Äù\n\nThere were no reported riches for Arnold because of his notoriety. Instead, he complained to Frank Brown, the Air Force investigator, ‚Äúthat his business had suffered greatly . at every stop in his business routes, large groups of people were waiting to question him .‚Äù\n\nBrown concluded his report, ‚ÄúMr. Arnold stated further that if he, at any time in the future, saw anything in the sky, to quote Mr. Arnold . ‚ÄòIf I ever saw a ten story building flying through the air I would never say a word about it,‚Äô due to the fact that he has been ridiculed by the press to such an extent that he is practically a moron in the eye of the majority of the population of the United States.‚Äù\n\nA mystery to this day\n\nDespite that statement to Brown, in the coming years Arnold was driven to prove he was right.\n\nThere were ‚Äúmany long hours of fruitless flying with a camera, trying and failing to find anything like his saucers again,‚Äù says Martin Shough, a well-regarded researcher of the UFO phenomena who has written a detailed analysis of Arnold‚Äôs account.\n\nIn an email, Shough, who lives in the Highlands of Scotland, says, ‚ÄúI am resigned to never knowing what Arnold saw.‚Äù\n\nHe concludes, ‚ÄúSeventy years on, when so much of the flying saucer mythology that Kenneth Arnold triggered has been explained away, it is somewhat embarrassing that Arnold‚Äôs own sighting remains obstinately resistant.\n\n‚ÄúBut there it is.‚Äù	2017-06-26 23:36:09.133179+03	0	0	0	0	\N	\N	6	1107	['The Washington Times Http', 'Erik Lacitis']
