th five, also taking home album of the year for ‚ÄúLemonade,‚Äù best female R&B/pop artist and video director of the year for ‚ÄúSorry.‚Äù\n\nSolange, Beyonce‚Äôs younger sister, also had a big night: She won the Centric award and called Sunday ‚Äúthe best birthday ever‚Äù (she turned 31 on Saturday).\n\n‚ÄúMy arm pits are sweating so much right now,‚Äù said Solange, who thanked BET for showing her ‚Äúqueens‚Äù like Aaliyah, Missy Elliott, Erykah Badu and others during her teenage years.\n\nSolange held a moment of silence later on, and the show also honored some of the minorities who died at the hands of police officers, including Trayvon Martin, Philando Castile, Eric Garner and others.\n\nOther winners included gospel rapper Lecrae and Migos, who took home best group. The hip-hop trio also won over the audience with its performances of the hits ‚ÄúBad and Boujee,‚Äù ‚ÄùT-Shirt‚Äù and ‚ÄúCongratulations,‚Äù with Post Malone. Chance the Rapper, and his mom, danced during the long set; as did Queen Latifah, Cardi B., ‚ÄúStranger Things‚Äù actor Caleb McLaughlin and ‚Äúblack-ish‚Äù actress Yara Shahidi, who won the YoungStars award.\n\nThough most of the performances were upbeat, others charmed with slower songs: Tamar Braxton and Maxwell gave vocally impressive performances, and Mary J. Blige sang songs from ‚ÄúStrength of a Woman,‚Äù her recent album that includes emotional tunes about her divorce.\n\n‚ÄúMary J. got that break up body. Whoa,‚Äù screamed Jamie Foxx, who presented an award after Blige‚Äôs performance.\n\nLeslie Jones of ‚ÄúSaturday Night Live‚Äù hosted the four-hour show. El DeBarge and Kamasi Washignton performed ‚ÄúCareless Whisper‚Äù in honor George Michael, who died last year on Christmas Day, while Janelle Monae collaborator Roman GianArthur excitedly sang ‚ÄúJohnny B. Goode‚Äù in tribute to Chuck Berry, who died in March.\n\nNew York rapper Prodigy, who died last week, was remembered in words by his Mobb Deep partner Havoc and Lil Kim, who appe