ù Justice Thomas said. ‚ÄúToday‚Äôs compromise will burden executive officials with the task of deciding ‚Äîon peril of contempt ‚Äî whether individuals from the six affected nations who wish to enter the United States have a sufficient connection to a person or entity in this country.‚Äù\n\nImmigrant-rights groups were already arguing that nearly every potential refugee has a tie to the U.S. by dint of the fact that a resettlement agency in the U.S. is working on their case.\n\nSen. Charles E. Grassley, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, countered that the only exceptions are when someone ‚Äúhas a close familial relationship or has a formal, documented purpose for entering the United States, such as a job or acceptance at a college or university.‚Äù\n\nThose fights aside, the ruling is the first major legal victory for Mr. Trump, who had been blasted by lower courts ‚Äî chiefly Democratic-appointed judges ‚Äî for showing ‚Äúanimus‚Äù to Muslims and for failing to justify his national security concerns. The justices, though, said the president deserves deference when acting on national security concerns in immigration matters when dealing with people who don‚Äôt already have a tie to the U.S.\n\n‚ÄúThe Supreme Court did what the lower court judges would not ‚Äî treat President Trump like any other president with the ‚Äòpresumption of regularity,‚Äô‚Äù Josh Blackman, associate professor at South Texas College of Law, wrote on his blog. ‚ÄúThe Justices did not delve into the president‚Äôs twitter account, nor did they parse his campaign statements.‚Äù\n\nThe court scheduled the broader case as part of its next session that begins in October.\n\nThe justices, though, signaled they expect Mr. Trump to use the reprieve to quickly figure out new policies and to put them in place: ‚ÄúGiven the Government‚Äôs representations in this litigation concerning the resources required to complete the 20-day review, we fully expect that the relief we grant today will permit