1548	The Green Room: What words and phrases do you use most when working?		https://cdn.thestage.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/21164927/Screen-Shot-2017-06-21-at-16.46.jpg	https://www.thestage.co.uk/advice/the-green-room/2017/green-room-phrases-use-most-working-in-theatre/	\N	She has played leading roles at the RSC, worked on new plays and toured both national and internationally Ros Clifford is 30.\nBeryl ‚ÄòLook after each other.‚ÄôAdam ‚ÄòAre we likely to be working weekends?‚ÄôRos ‚ÄòLet me ask the question‚Äô.\nWhat phrases do we hear a lot from directors and what do we think of them?\nI cannot bear it, for example, when directors say, ‚ÄòShow me.‚Äô And they all do say it at some point.\nJon Well, that‚Äôs directors sorted.	Meet our panel: We have given our panellists pen-names and used stock images but their biographies reflect their real career details...\n\nAlbert Parker is 60 and has appeared as a regular in soaps, two BAFTA award winning sitcoms, theatre and TV Vivian Lee is 38 and has played leading roles at the National, the RSC and the Royal Court, alongside regular TV appearances Adam Lovett, 45, has appeared in Oscar-winning films, on TV and in theatre at the RSC, National Theatre, and the West End Rosemary Crackers is 50 and has worked extensively in TV, film and theatre for nearly 30 years Beryl Phoenix is in her 40s. She has played leading roles at the RSC, worked on new plays and toured both national and internationally Ros Clifford is 30. Currently a deputy stage manager, she has worked extensively in London and regional theatre for nine years Ivan Low, 47, a production manager, has worked widely in the UK and abroad with regional and national theatre, opera and dance companies\n\nBeryl ‚ÄòStory, story, story.‚Äô\n\nVivian ‚ÄòWhere is the green room?‚Äô, ‚ÄòWhat‚Äôs the Wi-Fi code?‚Äô, ‚ÄòI‚Äôve had 34 cups of coffee, I‚Äôm bringing in the herbals tomorrow‚Äô followed by ‚ÄòI have a splitting headache.‚Äô\n\nAdam Marc Warren said in an interview I read that the two things actors care about the most are coffee and Wi-Fi.\n\nBeryl ‚ÄòLook after each other.‚Äô\n\nAdam ‚ÄòAre we likely to be working weekends?‚Äô\n\nRos ‚ÄòLet me ask the question‚Äô. ‚ÄòNo.‚Äô ‚ÄòFor fuck‚Äôs sake.‚Äô\n\nBeryl Yes, various swear words, certainly.\n\nAlbert ‚ÄòObviously I‚Äôm just doing this to be seen‚Ä¶‚Äô\n\nBeryl ‚ÄòWe‚Äôre not in Aleppo, it‚Äôs only a play‚Äô.\n\nRosemary I mostly use the phrases ‚Äòoff book‚Äô ‚Äì as in ‚ÄòI have two hopes of being off book for this beast‚Äô ‚Äì ‚Äòthe fear‚Äô ‚Äì as in ‚Äòstop mentioning when we tech, it‚Äôs giving me the fear‚Äô ‚Äì and ‚ÄòEquity dep‚Äô ‚Äì as in ‚ÄòI‚Äôm not being Equity dep, I did it last time.‚Äô\n\nIvan ‚ÄòWang‚Äô is popular among some technical staff. Used when, for a reason unknown, something happens in your favour that really shouldn‚Äôt. ‚ÄòThat‚Äôs lighting wang!‚Äô\n\nJon In my experience, the one thing that is guaranteed on any job is that in every dressing room ever, on any night, someone will say: ‚ÄòHave we had the five?‚Äô\n\nVivian ‚ÄòI promised myself I wouldn‚Äôt start smoking again.‚Äô\n\nAlbert ‚ÄòI knew this scene in the bath.‚Äô To which the standard director‚Äôs retort is: ‚ÄòWell, what a shame you didn‚Äôt bring the bath into the rehearsal room.‚Äô\n\nVivian ‚ÄòIt‚Äôs harder when you only have one line.‚Äô\n\nIvan ‚ÄòBespoke solutions‚Äô is one of my golden phrases. I was asked by one director what my plan was for a mobile ladder to move around safely on a raked stage with an actor at the top of it. ‚ÄúAh, that will be a bespoke solution,‚Äù says I. In reality, I hadn‚Äôt a clue how it would work. In the end it did, thankfully. Bespoke solutions. I should have the T-shirt made.\n\nJon Ah yes, what about our beloved lords and ladies, masters and mistresses? What phrases do we hear a lot from directors and what do we think of them? I cannot bear it, for example, when directors say, ‚ÄòShow me.‚Äô And they all do say it at some point.\n\nAlbert ‚ÄòWith respect...‚Äô as your considered creative initiative is about to be totally quashed.\n\nIvan ‚ÄòCreative‚Äô. I‚Äôve fallen foul of that word. I once discussed allocating time for the ‚Äòcreatives‚Äô ‚Äì the lighting and sound designers, choreographers and so on ‚Äì to give notes over and above the director‚Äôs feedback. My colleague reminded me that the cast, crew, dressers, flymen and voice coach were all creatives and I should watch how I describe the staff. Quite correct, too.\n\nAdam Someone who worked with Emma Rice told me that when she doesn‚Äôt like what you‚Äôre doing she says: ‚ÄúStrong. But wrong.‚Äù\n\nAlbert That‚Äôs what the board at Shakespeare‚Äôs Globe thought, too.\n\nAdam Or when they describe the character as ‚Äòlike this‚Äô. I want to say, ‚ÄòI know what he‚Äôs like, but that doesn‚Äôt help me get there.‚Äô\n\nAlbert As I say to younger actors: just say ‚Äòyes‚Äô, then get on with doing what you want.\n\nAdam I was in a show once that ended with a lingering look from me as I shut the door at the end of the play. The renowned director waited until the dress rehearsal before giving me the note: ‚ÄúCould you do it a little less as if you were taking in The Cherry Orchard for the last time?‚Äù\n\nJon While we‚Äôre on the subject of directors, what do we think of line readings? Are we for or against? They used to be so totally taboo, but some actors seem to like them now.\n\nVivian If nothing else is hitting, then I say yes.\n\nAdam I bloody love a line reading, as long as it‚Äôs a good one. But then I tend to think quite musically, so I love being told how it should sound. I think it messes up actors who don‚Äôt think that way.\n\nAlbert I usually just say: ‚ÄòTell me how to say it and I‚Äôll make it my own.‚Äô That seems to work.\n\nJon Well, that‚Äôs directors sorted. How about other actors? What are the things you‚Äôre always hearing from colleagues?\n\nAlbert ‚ÄòAre you actually going to do it like that on the night?‚Äô\n\nAdam ‚ÄòIf you do